@startuml gkg_selfmanaged_auth_sequence

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam padding 5
skinparam roundCorner 8
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title Hybrid Self-Managed: Auth Flow\n(Cloud-hosted GKG ↔ On-Prem Monolith)

box "Customer On-Premises" #FFF3E0
  actor "User /\nLLM Agent" as user
  participant "GitLab Rails\n(Self-Managed)" as rails
  participant "Gitaly" as gitaly
end box

box "GitLab Cloud Infrastructure" #E8F4FD
  participant "DAP\n(Data Access Proxy)" as dap
  participant "Orbit\n(Graph Query Engine)" as orbit
  database "ClickHouse\nCloud" as ch
end box

== Query Request ==

user -> rails : Graph query request
rails -> dap : HTTP + JWT\n(identity, scopes,\nallowed traversal paths)
dap -> orbit : Forwarded request\n(validated JWT)

== Authorization (in-process, from JWT) ==

orbit -> orbit : Read allowed traversal paths\nfrom JWT (Claims.group_traversal_ids)
note right #FFCCCC
  **Challenge 1: Network connectivity**
  The JWT is minted on-prem by the customer's
  Rails; the cross-boundary hop that remains is
  the row-level redaction callback (below), which
  Orbit makes back to on-prem Rails. Requires a
  stable, low-latency path across the customer
  firewall — a secure tunnel (VPN, Private Link,
  or reverse proxy).
end note
orbit -> orbit : Inject traversal_path\nfilter into SQL

== Query Execution ==

orbit -> ch : Parameterized SQL query
ch --> orbit : Result set

orbit --> dap : Query response
dap --> rails : Response
rails --> user : Graph data

== Batch Redaction (row-level) ==

orbit -> rails : RedactionRequired (gRPC stream)\n//resource_type + abilities ("read")//\n//Crosses the network boundary//
note right #FFCCCC
  **Challenge 2: Latency**
  This cross-boundary redaction round-trip to
  on-prem Rails adds 10-100ms+ per batch and,
  under load, can dominate query time.

  **Challenge 3: Redaction at scale**
  Every result set may require a round-trip to
  on-prem Rails for row-level permission filtering.
  Batching helps but doesn't eliminate the call.
end note

rails --> orbit : Authorized resource set
orbit --> dap : Final filtered response
dap --> rails : Response
rails --> user : Redacted graph data

== Key Risks ==

note over user, ch #FFE0E0
  **Summary of cross-boundary auth challenges:**

  1. **Firewall / network policy** — customer must allow the cloud → on-prem
     redaction callback (gRPC stream) to reach their Rails instance.
  2. **Latency budget** — every redaction round-trip crosses the network;
     large result sets amplify this and can spike P99.
  3. **Availability coupling** — if the on-prem monolith is unreachable,
     Orbit cannot redact results (fail-open is not acceptable).
  4. **Security posture** — exposing an auth endpoint externally increases
     attack surface; mutual TLS or equivalent is required.
end note

@enduml
